 the command line, providing the necessary instructions to leverage the full potential of the system's media handling capabilities.\r\n\n  Line 23: This directory contains the complete and detailed documentation for the `mediatool`, a system built-in, lightweight command-line toolset specifically created for operating and managing media library resources on the device. The content within this directory is structured to provide a holistic understanding of the tool, starting with a comprehensive introduction that outlines its purpose and capabilities. It includes extensive usage guidance and detailed command-line instructions that cover every aspect of media asset management. Users will find specific references for importing media into the library, exporting assets for backup or analysis, querying the database to retrieve specific media information, and deleting obsolete or test files. Additionally, the documentation covers critical maintenance tasks such as database resets, which are vital for clearing data during testing cycles. Because the tool is accessed via the `hdc shell` and requires no additional software installation, it offers a highly efficient and accessible solution for command-line interaction. This documentation is primarily tailored for developers and testers who need to perform high-level debugging and management of media data, ensuring they can execute complex operations with speed and accuracy directly from the terminal.\n\nD:\\workspace\\Foodike\\.agents\\skills\\cangjie-harmonyos-doc-search\\harmonyos-6.1-8k\\Guide\\tools\\cj-hidumper\\.overview.md:\n  Line 20: The content encompasses a wide range of functionalities essential for system maintenance. It includes instructions for querying basic system information, monitoring the real-time status of core services, and collecting detailed performance data statistics. Users can leverage these commands to gather specific metrics regarding CPU usage, memory consumption, and network activity. Additionally, the directory covers advanced memory analysis techniques, allowing for deeper inspection of system resources.\r\n\n\nD:\\workspace\\Foodike\\.agents\\skills\\cangjie-harmonyos-doc-search\\harmonyos-6.1-8k\\Guide\\tools\\cj-hdc\\.overview.md:\n  Line 3: The `cj-hdc` directory encompasses the essential documentation for the OpenHarmony Device Connector (HDC), a powerful command-line utility tailored for the OpenHarmony ecosystem. It is designed to assist developers and technical personnel in establishing a seamless connection between a PC and OpenHarmony devices for debugging and interaction purposes. The directory covers a broad spectrum of topics, ranging from the tool's architectural design and initial environment setup to advanced command-line operations. Core features documented include file transfer mechanisms, port forwarding capabilities, and comprehensive device management protocols. Additionally, it provides vital resources for troubleshooting, such as error code lookups and connection issue resolution. This documentation is highly suitable for HarmonyOS/OpenHarmony developers, quality assurance testers, and technical support teams who require a reliable reference to optimize their debugging workflows and ensure efficient device communication.\r\n\n\nD:\\workspace\\Foodike\\.agents\\skills\\cangjie-harmonyos-doc-search\\harmonyos-6.1-8k\\Guide\\tools\\cj-bm-tool\\.overview.md:\n  Line 15:     *   Configure Overlay resources for customization → See `bm工具/`\r\n\n\nD:\\workspace\\Foodike\\.agents\\skills\\cangjie-harmonyos-doc-search\\harmonyos-6.1-8k\\Guide\\tools\\cj-atm-tool\\atm工具\\查询命令\\查询命令_1.md:\n  Line 70: atm dump -t -b ohos.telephony.resources\r\n\n  Line 77: #   \"bundleName\": \"ohos.telephony.resources\",\r\n\n\nD:\\workspace\\Foodike\\.agents\\skills\\cangjie-harmonyos-doc-search\\harmonyos-6.1-8k\\Guide\\tools\\.overview.md:\n  Line 3: This directory serves as a centralized repository for a comprehensive suite of command-line tools designed for the OpenHarmony and HarmonyOS ecosystems. It covers a wide range of functionalities including application lifecycle management, system debugging, performance analysis, and resource handling. The collection includes essential utilities like the Bundle Manager (bm), HiLog, and HDC, alongside specialized tools for account management, power control, and media processing. These resources are primarily intended for developers, QA engineers, and system integrators seeking to streamline development workflows, diagnose system issues, and optimize application performance.\r\n\n  Line 13: - Handle resources, media, and packaging → [15] cj-mediatool, [16] cj-packing-tool, [17] cj-param-tool, [19] cj-restool, [20] cj-toybox, [21] cj-unpacking-tool\r\n\n\nD:\\workspace\\Foodike\\.agents\\skills\\cangjie-harmonyos-doc-search\\harmonyos-6.1-8k\\Guide\\telephony\\.overview.md:\n  Line 3: This directory serves as a comprehensive resource hub for the Telephony Kit, specifically focusing on cellular communication services. It is designed to assist developers in integrating fundamental calling capabilities into their applications, with a primary emphasis on the \"Make Call\" functionality. The content covers the Beta version of the component, providing essential architectural insights and technical documentation. It is particularly suitable for developers working with the Cangjie language who need to implement voice communication features. By utilizing these resources, developers can efficiently access cellular services, understand system constraints, and build stable, reliable calling applications for mobile environments.\r\n\n\nD:\\workspace\\Foodike\\.agents\\skills\\cangjie-harmonyos-doc-search\\harmonyos-6.1-8k\\Guide\\security\\UniversalKeystoreKit\\cj-huks-key-derivation\\密钥派生\\开发案例\\.overview.md:\n  Line 20: This directory focuses on the implementation of the PBKDF2 (Password-Based Key Derivation Function 2) algorithm, utilizing the Cangjie language and HUKS interfaces. The documentation guides developers through the complexities of defining key parameters and executing the three-stage derivation process: initialization, update, and completion. It emphasizes the complete lifecycle management of keys to maintain security integrity. Critical technical elements discussed include configuring the AES algorithm, utilizing SHA256 for message digests, handling salt values to prevent rainbow table attacks, and setting appropriate iteration counts to enhance security. These resources are invaluable for developers aiming to build secure key derivation solutions in HarmonyOS, providing the necessary foundation to protect sensitive user data with strong password-based encryption.\n\nD:\\workspace\\Foodike\\.agents\\skills\\cangjie-harmonyos-doc-search\\harmonyos-6.1-8k\\Guide\\security\\UniversalKeystoreKit\\cj-huks-key-anon-attestation\\.overview.md:\n  Line 3: This directory focuses on the implementation of anonymous key attestation using the Hardware Universal Key Store (HUKS) within the Cangjie programming environment. It provides comprehensive resources for developers looking to enhance key security through attestation mechanisms without revealing identity. The content covers development guides, parameter configurations, interface logic, and practical code examples. Key topics include HUKS, anonymous attestation, and key security. This material is specifically designed for application developers who require secure key proof capabilities and possess a basic understanding of HUKS API interactions.\r\n\n\nD:\\workspace\\Foodike\\.agents\\skills\\cangjie-harmonyos-doc-search\\harmonyos-6.1-8k\\Guide\\security\\UniversalKeystoreKit\\cj-huks-key-anon-attestation\\.abstract.md:\n  Line 1: This directory focuses on the implementation of anonymous key attestation using the Hardware Universal Key Store (HUKS) within the Cangjie programming environment. It provides comprehensive resources for developers looking to enhance key security throug...\n\nD:\\work